subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis:
Body size and coloration patterns of this species are variable, but female mandible of the species fivetoothed (
Fig. 7c
), T5–T6 with teeth laterally (
Fig. 7f
), the female clypeus completely yellow (
Fig. 7b
), the yellow maculations on T1–T5 wide and long (
Fig. 7e
), T6 with large yellow maculations (
Fig. 7f
); male, lateral margins on T2–T4 scarcely protuberant, without distinct tufts (
Fig. 8e
), apical process of S8 narrowly triangular (
Fig. 8h
), the lateral spine of T5 yellow (
Fig. 8f
). This combination of characters can be used to distinguish this species from other 

Anthidium

species.

